<!-- ============================================================
     MODULE 1: WHAT YOUR SCORE MEANS
     ============================================================ -->
<div class="apn-e-section" id="apn-e-m1">
  <div class="apn-e-wrap">

    <span class="apn-e-label">Module 01: 2 min</span>
    <div class="apn-e-divider"></div>
    <h2 class="apn-e-h2">What Your Score Means.</h2>

    <p class="apn-e-body apn-e-body-lg">
      A score of 86 to 100 places you in the Elite tier. This is a real distinction. In the full dataset of athletes who complete this assessment, Elite-tier athletes represent the top 15 to 20%. The foundation here is not just present, it is sophisticated. Training is programmed with periodization. Protein is distributed across multiple meals. Sleep is protected and tracked. Supplementation has a hierarchy.
    </p>

    <p class="apn-e-body">
      This creates a specific challenge that lower-tier athletes do not face. When all primary gaps are functionally closed, the obvious levers are gone. The remaining gains exist, but they require precision instruments to find: bloodwork markers, sleep stage architecture, micronutrient accuracy to the specific nutrient level, and HRV-informed training load management. These are not accessible to athletes who haven't closed the primary gaps. You have. That's why they're relevant now.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-e-data-callout">
      <div class="stat" id="apn-e-score-display">91</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Your Elite Score: Top 15 to 20% of all athletes assessed</div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-e-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">What Defines the Elite Tier</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      Elite athletes do not guess at their training. Progressive overload is planned. Deloads are scheduled. Protein is distributed across four or more meals, each exceeding the leucine threshold of approximately 3g per meal required to trigger a maximal muscle protein synthesis response. Sleep is consistent: a fixed wake time within 15 minutes seven days a week, room temperature controlled to 65 to 68 degrees Fahrenheit, and caffeine cutoff before noon. Supplementation is tiered: creatine and protein as the non-negotiable foundation, then sleep quality support, then cortisol management, then micronutrient precision.
    </p>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      At this tier, you are not building. You are optimizing a system that already functions. The standard shifts from "does it work" to "how precisely can it work."
    </p>

    <div class="apn-e-warning">
      <span class="apn-e-warning-label">Gap to Champion Tier</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;color:#4C1D95;">
        The Champion tier (a framework used in advanced performance assessments) operates on variables that require medical and laboratory access: testosterone optimization, VO2max testing, lactate threshold work, comprehensive bloodwork panels, and periodized nutrition at precise caloric and macronutrient targets. To reach that tier from Elite requires not just better habits, but data that most athletes cannot generate without professional support. The coaching option in this MasterClass is the bridge between Elite protocol and Champion-level precision.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-e-h3">Where Most Elite Athletes Get Stuck</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      The Elite plateau is subtle and specific. It is not caused by lack of effort. It is caused by novelty-seeking. Elite athletes, accustomed to results from new protocols, begin chasing new training methods, new supplements, or new approaches the moment their current system stops producing visible change. This breaks the compound effect of an established, functioning system.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-e-pull-quote">
      <p>"The margin is small. The details are everything. Compound precision, not change."</p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-e-h3">One Immediate Insight</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      At 86 to 100, the question shifts from "what should I add" to "what can I optimize." The remaining gains are in the variables you are currently not measuring: specific bloodwork markers, sleep stage quality, micronutrient sufficiency at the individual nutrient level, and HRV trend over training blocks. This MasterClass gives you the framework to access all four.
    </p>

  </div>
</div>


<!-- ============================================================
     MODULE 2: THE ELITE PERFORMANCE PROFILE
     ============================================================ -->
<div class="apn-e-section-alt" id="apn-e-m2">
  <div class="apn-e-wrap">

    <span class="apn-e-label">Module 02: 5 min</span>
    <div class="apn-e-divider"></div>
    <h2 class="apn-e-h2">The Elite Performance Profile.</h2>

    <p class="apn-e-body apn-e-body-lg">
      Every tier has a signature. The Elite signature is systematization. The behavioral difference between Elite and Competitor is not motivation or discipline. It is structure. Elite athletes have replaced habits with systems: self-correcting, data-informed, and resistant to the disruptions of travel, stress, and schedule variation.
    </p>

    <!-- 3 defining behaviors -->
    <h3 class="apn-e-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">Three Defining Elite Behaviors</h3>
    <ol class="apn-e-number-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Systematized performance across all pillars.</strong> Elite athletes do not rely on motivation to execute their sleep protocol, protein targets, or training plan. Each pillar runs as a system with defined inputs, measurable outputs, and a review process. When travel disrupts one element, the system has a protocol for that. When a training session is missed, the system has a protocol for that too. Systems do not depend on feeling ready.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Data-informed decisions on training and recovery.</strong> HRV (heart rate variability) monitoring is a standard part of the Elite daily routine. A declining HRV trend over five or more consecutive days is a reliable signal of under-recovery and predicts performance decrement before the athlete subjectively feels it. Training logs show consistent progressive overload: each cycle builds on the last. Sleep trackers reveal quality, not just duration. Elite athletes make decisions from data, not just feel.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Diminishing marginal returns as the operating reality.</strong> This is not a criticism. It is a fact of high-level performance. The first month of consistent creatine use produces larger gains than month twelve. The first year of structured training produces larger strength adaptation than year four. Elite athletes understand this and do not interpret smaller gains as a signal to change everything. They interpret it as a signal to increase precision. Smaller inputs, tighter execution, and accurate targeting of the remaining variable.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <!-- Separator from Champion -->
    <hr class="apn-e-hr">
    <h3 class="apn-e-h3">What Separates Elite from the Next Level</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      The athletes operating beyond Elite are not training harder. They are operating with laboratory-grade data. Comprehensive bloodwork panels reveal specific deficiencies that are invisible to self-assessment: sub-optimal ferritin affecting oxygen-carrying capacity, low Vitamin D suppressing testosterone and immune function, magnesium deficiency reducing sleep quality and muscle function, zinc insufficiency limiting anabolic hormone production. These variables are real, measurable, and correctable. They require data to find.
    </p>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      Elite athletes who access this data and act on it consistently report performance improvements in areas that seemed plateaued. The mechanism is not new. The data precision is.
    </p>

    <!-- Most common mistake -->
    <div class="apn-e-warning">
      <span class="apn-e-warning-label">Most Common Elite Mistake</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;color:#4C1D95;">
        Seeking novelty instead of compounding what is working. When gains slow at Elite level, the instinct is to change the protocol: new training split, new supplement, new diet approach. This instinct is wrong. It breaks the compound effect of an established system and resets adaptation timelines. The research on long-term training adaptation consistently shows that athletes who maintain system consistency for twelve or more months outperform athletes who rotate protocols every three to six months, even when the rotated protocols are individually superior. The compound effect requires continuity. Precision beats novelty at Elite.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Precision callout -->
    <div class="apn-e-data-callout">
      <div class="stat">86+</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Where precision replaces effort as the primary performance lever</div>
    </div>

    <!-- Compounding opportunity -->
    <h3 class="apn-e-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">The Precision Opportunity</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      At Elite, the compounding opportunity is in stacked precision. Each variable optimized independently produces a small gain. Those small gains: sleep architecture, micronutrient sufficiency, HRV-informed training load, supplement timing precision: compound into a meaningful performance increment when executed simultaneously for a sustained period. The window here is not days or weeks. It is months. Elite athletes who commit to a twelve-week precision protocol consistently report 8 to 15% improvements in objective performance metrics.
    </p>

