<!-- ============================================================
     MODULE 4: THE ELITE PRIORITY FRAMEWORK
     ============================================================ -->
<div class="apn-e-section-alt" id="apn-e-m4">
  <div class="apn-e-wrap">

    <span class="apn-e-label">Module 04: 10 min</span>
    <div class="apn-e-divider"></div>
    <h2 class="apn-e-h2">The Elite Priority Framework.</h2>

    <!-- Mental model -->
    <p class="apn-e-body apn-e-body-lg">
      The Elite mental model operates on a single principle: optimize, do not reinvent. At this tier, the system is already functioning. The task is to execute it with greater precision, not to replace it with something new. Every decision flows from this principle: compound what is working, add precision to what is already producing results, and resist the pull of novelty.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-e-pull-quote">
      <p>"The margin is small. The details are everything. Compound precision, not change."</p>
    </div>

    <p class="apn-e-body">
      At Elite level, the question shifts in every domain. In training: not "should I train harder" but "is my load periodized optimally relative to my HRV trend." In nutrition: not "am I hitting protein" but "is each meal clearing the leucine threshold." In sleep: not "am I getting enough hours" but "is my sleep architecture producing adequate slow-wave and REM percentages." In supplementation: not "what should I add" but "is my current stack dosed and timed for maximum bioavailability."
    </p>

    <h3 class="apn-e-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">The 4-Week Elite Protocol</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">Four weeks. Four precision audits. Each week targets one variable that most athletes at this level have never directly measured.</p>

    <!-- Week 1 -->
    <div class="apn-e-week-block">
      <span class="apn-e-week-label">Week 1: Full Data Audit</span>
      <p style="margin:0 0 12px 0;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#0D0D0D;">Focus: Establish baseline data across all primary performance variables before making any protocol changes.</p>
      <ul class="apn-e-checklist">
        <li>Pull your HRV data from the last 30 days if tracked. Identify the trend: rising, stable, or declining. A declining trend in the absence of deliberate deload means cumulative fatigue is accumulating faster than it is being cleared.</li>
        <li>Request a basic bloodwork panel if not completed in the last six months. Priority markers: Vitamin D (target above 50 ng/mL), Zinc (target above 80 mcg/dL), Magnesium (RBC magnesium preferred over serum), Ferritin (target 50 to 150 ng/mL for males), Free Testosterone (target upper quartile for your age range).</li>
        <li>Review your training log for the last four weeks. Is there measurable progressive overload in your primary lifts or sport-specific metrics? If not, the periodization model needs adjustment, not more volume.</li>
        <li>No protocol changes this week. Observe and document only. Data first.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="apn-e-assignment">
      <span class="apn-e-assignment-label">Week 1 Assignment</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;">Document your HRV 30-day average, your last bloodwork values for the five markers listed, and your progressive overload trend for three primary training metrics. This is your Elite baseline. You cannot optimize what you have not measured. Return here with your data before starting Week 2.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Week 2 -->
    <div class="apn-e-week-block">
      <span class="apn-e-week-label">Week 2: Micronutrient Gaps and Stack Precision</span>
      <p style="margin:0 0 12px 0;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#0D0D0D;">Focus: Address specific micronutrient deficiencies revealed in Week 1 bloodwork. Lock supplement timing precision.</p>
      <ul class="apn-e-checklist">
        <li>If Vitamin D is below 50 ng/mL: 5,000 IU daily with a fat-containing meal. Vitamin D is fat-soluble. Without dietary fat, absorption drops by 30 to 50%.</li>
        <li>If Zinc is below 80 mcg/dL: 15 to 25mg elemental zinc (zinc glycinate or citrate preferred over oxide) taken away from calcium-rich foods. Zinc competes with calcium for absorption.</li>
        <li>If Ferritin is below 50 ng/mL: consult with a physician. Iron supplementation without confirmed deficiency has adverse effects and should not be self-prescribed.</li>
        <li>Lock supplement timing: Creatine at a consistent daily time. Protein post-training within 45 minutes. Magnesium glycinate 400mg 30 to 60 minutes before sleep. Ashwagandha with dinner. Omega-3 with the largest meal of the day for maximum EPA/DHA absorption.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="apn-e-assignment">
      <span class="apn-e-assignment-label">Week 2 Assignment</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;">Write your supplement timing schedule. Every product, every dose, every time. Put it in your phone. A supplement taken inconsistently or at the wrong time relative to meals and competing nutrients produces a fraction of its potential benefit. Precision in timing is free. Use it.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Week 3 -->
    <div class="apn-e-week-block">
      <span class="apn-e-week-label">Week 3: Sleep Architecture Protocol</span>
      <p style="margin:0 0 12px 0;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#0D0D0D;">Focus: Optimize sleep quality through environmental and behavioral precision. Track HRV response.</p>
      <ul class="apn-e-checklist">
        <li>Fix wake time within a 15-minute window, seven days per week. Weekend sleep schedule variation of more than one hour suppresses melatonin onset on Sunday night and reduces Monday sleep quality: a phenomenon called social jet lag. Consistent wake time is the single highest-leverage sleep variable.</li>
        <li>Set room temperature to 65 to 68 degrees Fahrenheit for sleep. Core body temperature must drop 1 to 3 degrees Fahrenheit to initiate sleep onset. A cool room accelerates this drop and increases time in deep (slow-wave) sleep by 10 to 15%.</li>
        <li>No caffeine after noon. Caffeine has a half-life of five to seven hours. A 200mg coffee at 2:00 PM means 100mg of caffeine is still active in your system at 7:00 to 9:00 PM, directly suppressing adenosine-driven sleep pressure.</li>
        <li>Track HRV this week. A sleep protocol optimized for architecture (not just duration) should produce a measurable HRV improvement within five to seven days of consistent execution.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="apn-e-assignment">
      <span class="apn-e-assignment-label">Week 3 Assignment</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;">Execute the full sleep protocol every night of Week 3. On Day 7, compare your HRV average to your Week 1 baseline. Any upward movement confirms the protocol is working. If your sleep tracker shows sleep stage data, note any change in deep sleep percentage. Deeper sleep means more growth hormone secretion, better next-day cortisol curve, and improved training output.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Scripture -->
    <div class="apn-e-scripture">
      <p>"Whatever you do, work at it with all your heart, as working for the Lord, not for human masters."</p>
      <cite>Colossians 3:23</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- Week 4 -->
    <div class="apn-e-week-block">
      <span class="apn-e-week-label">Week 4: Training Load Optimization</span>
      <p style="margin:0 0 12px 0;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#0D0D0D;">Focus: Adjust training load based on HRV trend data collected across Weeks 1 to 3.</p>
      <ul class="apn-e-checklist">
        <li>If your HRV trend is declining: execute a scheduled deload. Reduce training volume by 40 to 50% for seven days. Maintain training frequency and movement quality. Deloads are not rest weeks. They are precision recovery inputs that allow the nervous system to catch up to accumulated training stress.</li>
        <li>If your HRV trend is stable or rising: add training volume incrementally. A 5 to 10% volume increase per training cycle is the maximum that supports continued adaptation without excessive fatigue accumulation.</li>
        <li>Review performance metrics from the last 30 days versus the 30-day baseline established in Week 1. Are key performance indicators moving in the right direction? Strength, power output, sport-specific pace, or conditioning markers?</li>
        <li>Build your Week 5 plan before Week 4 ends. The plan is simple: continue the sleep protocol, maintain supplement timing precision, and apply the training load decision made in Week 4.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="apn-e-assignment">
      <span class="apn-e-assignment-label">Week 4 Assignment</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;">Answer three questions before Week 4 ends. First: Is your HRV trend positive, stable, or negative? Second: Which training load decision does your HRV data support (deload or volume increase)? Third: What is the single highest-precision variable you identified this month that you were previously not measuring? That variable is your precision focus for the next training block.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- What Champion requires -->
    <h3 class="apn-e-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">What the Next Level Requires</h3>
    <p class="apn-e-body">
      Moving beyond Elite requires laboratory data, professional coaching, and the willingness to operate on variables that most athletes never access. Bloodwork-driven micronutrient protocols, HRV-informed periodization, body composition scanning, lactate threshold testing, and comprehensive hormonal assessment are the instruments of the next level. These are not available through self-assessment alone. They require a coach who works at this level of precision. That option is in Module 7.
    </p>

  </div>
</div>


